<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Makes a Seed Gift Box Actually Useful</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Practical crop selection.</strong> The seeds should match what people actually grow and eat, not just what sounds interesting.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Reliable performance.</strong> Germination and consistency matter more than how many packets are included.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Balanced variety.</strong> A mix of quick crops and staple vegetables increases the chance everything gets used.
  </p>

  <p>
    A good box supports a real garden plan instead of creating extra decisions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Some Seed Gift Boxes Go Unused</h2>

  <p>
    Many gift boxes focus too heavily on novelty.
  </p>

  <p>
    That often leads to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>unfamiliar or difficult crops</li>
    <li>varieties that do not fit the gardener’s space</li>
    <li>seeds that never get planted</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Even well-packaged collections can end up sitting unused if they do not match real gardening needs.
  </p>
</section>

